the blessed Jesus Christ, we having come to the setting of the sun and
beholding the evening light, praise God, Father, Son, and Holy Ghost. 
It is meet at all times that thou shouldest be hymned with auspicious
voices, Son of God, Giver of Life:  wherefore the world glorifieth
thee.”

<span id="fn_1325"></span>[46:1326](2080059.htm#fr_1325.md) <span
id="vii.xxx-p25.4"></span>

<span id="vii.xxx-p26"></span> Identified by some with two early hymns,
<span class="Greek"><span id="vii.xxx-p26.1"></span>Δόξα ἐν
ὑψίστοις</span>, and <span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.xxx-p26.2"></span>φῶς ἱλαρόν</span>.

<span id="fn_1326"></span>[46:1327](2080059.htm#fr_1326.md) <span
id="vii.xxx-p26.3"></span>

<span id="vii.xxx-p27"></span> The <span class="c14"><span
id="vii.xxx-p27.1"></span>mss.</span> vary between <span
class="Greek"><span id="vii.xxx-p27.2"></span>ἐ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="vii.xxx-p27.3"></span>ξιτήριον</span> and <span
class="Greek"><span id="vii.xxx-p27.4"></span>ἀ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="vii.xxx-p27.5"></span>λεξιτήριον</span>,
farewell gift and amulet or charm.  In *Ep*. cciii. 299 Basil says that
our Lord gave His disciples peace as an <span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.xxx-p27.6"></span>ἐ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.xxx-p27.7"></span>ξιτήριον δῶρον</span>, using the word, but in
conjunction with <span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.xxx-p27.8"></span>δῶρον</span>.  Greg. Naz., *Orat*. xiv. 223
speaks of our Lord leaving peace “<span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.xxx-p27.9"></span>ὥ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="vii.xxx-p27.10"></span>σπερ ἄλλο τι ἐξιτήριον</span>.”

<span id="fn_1327"></span>[46:1328](2080059.htm#fr_1327.md) <span
id="vii.xxx-p28.1"></span>

<span id="vii.xxx-p29"></span> *i.e*. Gregory, bishop of Neocæsarea,
known as Gregorius Thaumaturgus, or Gregory the Wonder-worker.  To the
modern reader “Gregory the Great” more naturally suggests Gregory of
Nazianzus, but this he hardly was to his friend and contemporary, though
the title had accrued to him by the time of the accepted Ephesine
Council in 431 (*vide* Labbe, vol. iv. p. 1192) Gregory the
Wonder-worker, † c. 270.

<span id="fn_1328"></span>[47:1329](2080059.htm#fr_1328.md) <span
id="vii.xxx-p29.1"></span>

