18](../../../bib/kjv/co2012.htm#018.md)<span id="vii.xxx-p30.1"></span>.

<span id="fn_1329"></span>[47:1330](2080059.htm#fr_1329.md) <span
id="vii.xxx-p30.2"></span>

<span id="vii.xxx-p31"></span> [Rom. i.
5](../../../bib/kjv/rom001.htm#005.md)<span id="vii.xxx-p31.1"></span>.

<span id="fn_1330"></span>[47:1331](2080059.htm#fr_1330.md) <span
id="vii.xxx-p31.2"></span>

<span id="vii.xxx-p32"></span> *e.g.*according to the legend, the
Lycus.  *cf*. Newman, *Essays on Miracles*, p. 267.

<span id="fn_1331"></span>[47:1332](2080059.htm#fr_1331.md) <span
id="vii.xxx-p32.1"></span>

<span id="vii.xxx-p33"></span> The story is told by Gregory of Nyssa,
*Life of Greg. Thaum*. Migne xlvi. 926–930.

<span id="fn_1332"></span>[47:1333](2080059.htm#fr_1332.md) <span
id="vii.xxx-p33.1"></span>

<span id="vii.xxx-p34"></span> The Neocæsareans appear to have
entertained a Puritan objection to the antiphonal psalmody becoming
general in the Church in the time of Basil.  *cf. Ep*. ccvii.

<span id="fn_1333"></span>[47:1334](2080059.htm#fr_1333.md) <span
id="vii.xxx-p34.1"></span>

<span id="vii.xxx-p35"></span> Firmilian, like Gregory the
Wonder-worker, a pupil of Origen, was bishop of Cæsarea from before
<span class="c14"><span id="vii.xxx-p35.1"></span>a.d.</span> 232
(Euseb. vi. 26) to 272 (Euseb. vii. 30).  By some his death at Tarsus is
placed in 264 or 5.

